definition: "Adiponectin is a protein hormone secreted exclusively by adipocytes (fat cells) that plays a central role in regulating glucose metabolism, fatty acid oxidation, and inflammatory signaling. Unlike most hormones that rise with increasing adipose tissue mass, adiponectin falls as adipose tissue — particularly visceral adipose tissue — expands. Adiponectin acts on multiple tissues via two receptors (AdipoR1 and AdipoR2): in skeletal muscle it promotes glucose uptake and fatty acid oxidation; in the liver it suppresses gluconeogenesis and reduces hepatic fat accumulation; in blood vessels it promotes endothelial function and suppresses vascular inflammation. High adiponectin is anti-inflammatory, insulin-sensitizing, and cardioprotective; low adiponectin is a reliable marker of metabolic dysfunction."
why_it_matters: "Adiponectin occupies a unique position in metabolic biology because it is simultaneously a cause and a consequence of metabolic health: it improves insulin sensitivity (and thus rising insulin sensitivity allows adiponectin to rise further), and its decline with visceral fat accumulation directly accelerates the metabolic and cardiovascular pathology of obesity. Low adiponectin independently predicts type 2 diabetes, metabolic syndrome, cardiovascular disease, and all-cause mortality — and it does so at earlier stages than conventional metabolic markers. It is also one of the few biomarkers that distinguishes metabolically healthy obesity from metabolically unhealthy obesity: obese individuals with preserved adiponectin have substantially better cardiometabolic outcomes than those with suppressed adiponectin, explaining why BMI alone is a poor predictor of metabolic disease."

